docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md:27:| A-023 | `GET /api/v1/dashboard/` uses the source-backed `management_readonly` scope as its dashboard-read permission and maps supported dashboard shells from the authenticated user's primary role: Credit Manager → `credit_manager`, CFO/Director → `sanction_committee`, Compliance Team Member/Company Secretary/Internal Auditor → `compliance`, Senior Manager Finance/CFC/Accounts Head → `treasury`, and Management Viewer or other dashboard-authorized roles → `management`. The catalogue seeds `management_readonly` for the dashboard role contexts implemented in 003G; it does not reuse report/export permissions or invent `dashboard.read`. 003G2 corrected the seed so `internal_auditor` (mapped to `compliance`) also holds `management_readonly`, closing the gap where its documented mapping returned `403`; a consistency test now asserts every role in `dashboard.services._ROLE_CONTEXTS` holds `management_readonly`. | `auth-permissions.md` §19.1 names `management_readonly` as dashboard/summary access, while the seeded §12 catalogue has report/compliance read permissions but no exact `dashboard.read` code. The API must still enforce 401/403 and return role-context shells without downstream calculations. | `docs/source/auth-permissions.md` §19.1; `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §43.1-§43.4; `docs/source/functional-spec.md` §12.2-§12.6; `docs/slices/003G-dashboard-task-summary-api.md` | 003G-dashboard-task-summary-api | Medium | Yes | 2026-07-05 | If source docs later add exact dashboard permission codes or role-specific dashboard scopes, replace `management_readonly` and update `sfpcl_credit/dashboard/services.py`, seed links, and tests. |
